# Building Mystic 1.10 A38 (fork)

This fork targets three platforms, each with its own build script and its own
set of prerequisites you must install first. Compiler: **Free Pascal (FPC) 2.6.2**
(the original A38 toolchain), CPU target **i386** (32-bit) on all three.

| Target            | Script             | Runs on           |
|-------------------|--------------------|-------------------|
| Windows (XP+)     | `build-win32.bat`  | Windows / cmd.exe |
| Linux (Debian)    | `build.sh`         | Linux / bash      |
| macOS (Darwin)    | `build-darwin.sh`  | macOS, or Linux w/ cross toolchain |

Run a script with no arguments to build every binary, or pass one target name
to build just that one (e.g. `./build.sh mis`).

> **macOS note:** the Darwin target is **i386 (32-bit Intel)** - a vintage target.
> This has real consequences for which Macs can run it and which SDK you need to
> link it. Before attempting a Mac build, read
> **"macOS target: processor eras and which SDK you need"** near the bottom of
> this file.

---

## Windows (XP and later) - `build-win32.bat`

**Prerequisites:**
- **FPC 2.6.2 for win32**, installed normally (the official installer). This
  ships every unit the build needs on its unit path (RTL + packages), so there
  is nothing else to fetch.

**Notes:**
- Produces PE32 i386 `.exe` files, console subsystem, MinSubsystemVersion 4.0
  (Win95/NT4+), so they run on Windows XP.
- No C glue and no package pre-builds are required on Windows.

---

## Linux (Debian 4/5 era, i386) - `build.sh`

**Prerequisites:**
- **FPC 2.6.2 for i386-linux** (matches the A38 toolchain). A *full* FPC install
  is expected because the MIS socket resolver pulls in **fcl-net (cnetdb)**, and
  the message/hash code uses **fcl-base / md5**; these ship with a complete FPC
  install and are found on the unit path automatically. If you installed only a
  minimal "base" component, add the missing unit dirs with `-Fu` in the script.
- **No C toolchain / resolver glue needed.** This fork uses a pure-Pascal
  address resolver, so the old `m_resolve_address.c` / `{$link ...o}` step is
  gone (the original C glue is kept only for reference in `attic/`). The Linux
  build is therefore pure FPC - no `cc` step.

**Notes (native i386 Debian):**
- On a real i386 Debian box the default linker and libc are already i386, so the
  plain script works with no extra flags.
- **Cross-linking i386 on an x86_64 host** (only relevant if you build on a
  64-bit machine): the linker may grab x86_64 crt objects. Add
  `-Xd -Fl/usr/lib32 -Fl/usr/lib/gcc/<triplet>/<ver>/32` so it finds the 32-bit
  runtime. This is a host quirk, not needed on a native i386 system.

---

## macOS / Darwin (i386) - `build-darwin.sh`

Darwin has two modes because the compile and link steps have different needs.

### Compile to Mach-O objects (works on ANY platform, incl. Linux, no Xcode)

**Prerequisites:**
- **FPC 2.6.2** with the **i386-darwin RTL units** available. If your FPC install
  lacks them, they cross-build from the FPC RTL source with FPC's *internal*
  Mach-O assembler (no external assembler / Xcode needed):
  ```
  cd <fpcsrc>/rtl/darwin
  make OS_TARGET=darwin CPU_TARGET=i386 FPC=<path>/ppc386 OPT="-Amacho"
  ```
  Then point the build at them with `DARWINUNITS=<...>/units/i386-darwin`.

Run compile-only:
```
COMPILE_ONLY=1 DARWINUNITS=/path/to/i386-darwin ./build-darwin.sh
```
This produces verified **Mach-O i386 objects** in `out_darwin/units/` but does
NOT link a runnable binary. `-Amacho` makes FPC use its internal Mach-O writer,
so no external assembler is required.

### Link a full runnable Mac binary

The final link needs a **Mach-O linker** and the **macOS system libraries** -
neither of which FPC 2.6.2 bundles, and neither of which exists on a plain Linux
box by default. Two ways to get a runnable binary:

1. **On a real Mac** - simplest. A Mac with Xcode / Command Line Tools already
   has Apple's linker (`ld64`) and the SDK. Just run `./build-darwin.sh` and it
   links normally.

2. **From Linux, with a cross toolchain** - no Mac needed at build time, but you
   must supply two things Apple owns:
   - **`ld64` / cctools built for Linux.** Apple open-sourced the linker
     (apple-opensource/ld64); the practical Linux ports are
     `tpoechtrager/cctools-port` or `osxcross`. Build it, then tell FPC where the
     linker lives with `-FD<path-to-cctools>/bin`.
   - **The macOS SDK libraries** (`crt1.o`, `libSystem`, frameworks). These are
     **Apple's** and must be copied from a Mac / an OS X install medium - they
     cannot be obtained on Linux alone. Point FPC's linker at the SDK root with
     `-XR<sdk-root>` (and `-Fl<sdk>/usr/lib`) so it links the correct startup
     objects instead of the host's.

   With both present, FPC drives the Darwin linker and produces a real Mac
   binary from Linux. This is the classic FPC "cross-compile to Darwin" setup.

**Why the split:** compilation is pure FPC (portable), but linking binds against
a specific OS's runtime. Mach-O compilation works anywhere; a *runnable* Mac
binary requires Apple's linker + SDK, by design.

---

## macOS target: processor eras and which SDK you need

This is the most misunderstood part of building the Mac version, so read it
before hunting for an SDK. The short version: **there is no single SDK that
covers "all Mac eras," and for our target you want an OLD one, not a new one.**

### Mac processor eras
- **PowerPC** (~1994-2006) - old; not a target here.
- **Intel x86 / x86-64** (2006-2020) - the middle era. "Intel Macs" are the
  OLDER/middle generation now, not the newest.
- **Apple Silicon / ARM** (M1, M2, M3, M4 - 2020-present) - the NEWEST Macs.

So newer Macs are **ARM**; Intel Macs are the older ones. Apple finished the
transition off Intel around 2022-2023.

### What our target is, and what can run it
This fork builds **i386-darwin = 32-bit Intel**. Consequences:
- **32-bit Intel Mac binaries stopped running on macOS after 10.15 Catalina
  (2019).** Apple removed all 32-bit support.
- A modern **ARM Mac cannot run a 32-bit Intel binary at all** - Rosetta 2
  translates 64-bit Intel only, never 32-bit.
- So an `i386-darwin` binary runs natively only on an **Intel Mac running
  pre-Catalina macOS** (roughly 10.6 - 10.14). That fits this project's vintage
  theme (Win XP 32-bit, Debian 4/5 i386, FPC 2.6.2), but set expectations
  accordingly.

### Which SDK to use (counterintuitive)
A **newer** SDK does **not** give wider backward compatibility - the opposite:
- **New macOS SDKs (11, 12, 13, 14, ...) dropped 32-bit entirely.** They CANNOT
  link an i386 binary. A modern SDK is useless for this target.
- For **i386 (32-bit Intel)** you need an **OLD SDK from the 32-bit Intel era**,
  around **MacOSX10.6 (Snow Leopard)** - this is exactly what the FPC cross-
  compile guides use (e.g. `-XR/opt/MacOSX10.6.sdk`). MacOSX10.5/10.6 are the
  safe choices for a 32-bit Intel build.

There is no SDK that spans both 32-bit Intel and ARM - they are mutually
exclusive worlds. Pick the SDK to match the target:
- **This project (i386, 32-bit Intel)** -> old SDK (~10.6 Snow Leopard).
- **A modern Mac (64-bit Intel or ARM)** -> a NEW SDK **and** a different FPC
  target (`x86_64-darwin` or `aarch64-darwin`) **and** a newer FPC. FPC 2.6.2
  (2013) predates Apple Silicon and cannot target ARM Macs.

### Where the old SDK comes from
The 10.5/10.6 SDKs shipped inside old Xcode (3.x/4.x) and on the retail Snow
Leopard install media - they are not on Apple's current download site. You
extract `MacOSX10.6.sdk` from an old Xcode / OS X install (do this once on a
Mac, or from install media), then copy it to your Linux box for cross-linking.
The `osxcross` project includes `gen_sdk_package.sh` to package an SDK for this
purpose. The SDK must contain `libSystem`, `crt1.o`, and the frameworks the
linker binds against.

A widely-used convenience source is the community repo **phracker/MacOSX-SDKs**
(github.com/phracker/MacOSX-SDKs), which hosts pre-extracted SDK folders from
`MacOSX10.1.5.sdk` through `MacOSX11.3.sdk` - including the 10.6 SDK this i386
target needs. It is the SDK source most osxcross guides point to.

**Licensing caveat, stated plainly:** these SDKs are Apple's copyrighted
material. Apple has never granted redistribution rights for them, so a repo that
re-hosts extracted SDKs sits in a tolerated-but-technically-infringing gray area
(Apple has historically not pursued such repos, but that is Apple declining to
enforce, not Apple granting permission). Using one is a decision for the person
doing the build to make with eyes open; the strictly-clean route is to extract
the SDK yourself from Apple tooling/media you own. This project neither bundles
nor redistributes any Apple SDK - the SDK is always the builder's own to supply.

### Cross-compile toolchain docs (for reference)
- **osxcross** (github.com/tpoechtrager/osxcross) - the practical "build macOS
  binaries from Linux" toolkit; bundles cctools-port (`ld64`) + SDK packaging.
- **cctools-port** (github.com/tpoechtrager/cctools-port) - the `ld64`/cctools
  Linux port itself.
- **phracker/MacOSX-SDKs** (github.com/phracker/MacOSX-SDKs) - pre-extracted
  macOS SDK folders (10.1.5 - 11.3); see the licensing caveat above.
- **FPC "Cross compiling to Darwin"** (FPC/Lazarus wiki + fpc-pascal list) - the
  FPC-specific flags: `-FD<cctools>/bin` (linker path), `-XR<sdk-root>` (SDK
  root), `-Fl<sdk>/usr/lib`.
- **Alternative with no Mac hardware:** a **GitHub Actions macOS runner** already
  has Xcode + SDK; for a GitHub-hosted repo you can build/link the Mac binary in
  CI on a real macOS runner, then publish it as a release artifact.

---

## Turnkey: cross-compiling Darwin binaries on your own Linux box

This is the concrete, step-by-step recipe. Everything here runs on **your**
Linux machine. The only Apple-owned piece is the SDK, which **you** supply in
Step 3 - it is never uploaded anywhere, it just sits on your disk.

### Step 1 - build the Mach-O linker (ld64 / cctools) for Linux
```
# deps (Debian/Ubuntu): clang, llvm, cmake, libssl-dev, uuid-dev, git
git clone https://github.com/tpoechtrager/apple-libtapi.git
cd apple-libtapi && INSTALLPREFIX=$HOME/cctools ./build.sh && ./install.sh && cd ..

git clone https://github.com/tpoechtrager/cctools-port.git
cd cctools-port/cctools
./configure --prefix=$HOME/cctools \
            --with-libtapi=$HOME/cctools \
            --target=i386-apple-darwin11
make && make install && cd ../..
# result: $HOME/cctools/bin/i386-apple-darwin11-ld  (this is ld64)
```

### Step 2 - have the i386-darwin FPC RTL units
If your FPC lacks them, cross-build from the FPC RTL source (no Xcode needed -
FPC's internal Mach-O writer via OPT="-Amacho"):
```
cd <fpcsrc>/rtl/darwin
make OS_TARGET=darwin CPU_TARGET=i386 FPC=<path>/ppc386 OPT="-Amacho"
# -> installs i386-darwin *.ppu units; note their path as DARWINUNITS
```

### Step 3 - supply the macOS SDK  *** YOUR PART ***
Obtain `MacOSX10.6.sdk` from your legal Snow Leopard / old-Xcode media (extract
it on a Mac, or with osxcross's gen_sdk_package.sh). Place it on your Linux box,
e.g. `/opt/MacOSX10.6.sdk`. It must contain `usr/lib/libSystem.*`, `usr/lib/
crt1.o`, and `System/Library/Frameworks`. (10.5 SDK also works for i386.)

### Step 4 - link a full Darwin binary
Point the compiler at (a) the Darwin RTL, (b) the ld64 you built, (c) your SDK:
```
ppc386 -Tdarwin -Pi386 -Mdelphi -O2 \
  -Fu<DARWINUNITS> \
  -Fumdl -Fumystic -Fimdl -Fimystic -Fomdl \
  -FD$HOME/cctools/bin \                 # where ld64 lives  (-FD)
  -XR/opt/MacOSX10.6.sdk \               # SDK root          (-XR)
  -Fl/opt/MacOSX10.6.sdk/usr/lib \       # SDK libs
  -FUout_darwin/units -FEout_darwin/bin \
  mystic/mystic.pas
```
`build-darwin.sh` accepts these via env vars once you've done Steps 1-3:
```
FPC=<ppc386> DARWINUNITS=<...> \
CCTOOLS=$HOME/cctools/bin SDKROOT=/opt/MacOSX10.6.sdk \
  ./build-darwin.sh
```
(Set COMPILE_ONLY=1 to skip linking and just verify Mach-O objects.)

### Gotchas (from the FPC cross-compile community)
- If the linker grabs the host's `/usr/lib/crt1.o` instead of the SDK's, your
  `-XR` SDK root isn't taking precedence - double-check the path and that the SDK
  actually contains `usr/lib/crt1.o`.
- Everything here is **i386 (32-bit Intel)** - runs on Intel Macs, pre-Catalina
  (10.6-10.14). See the processor-eras section above.
- Zero-hardware alternative: a **GitHub Actions macOS runner** already has the
  SDK + linker; build/link there in CI and publish the binary as a release.

---

## Period-correct toolchain matrix (build it all with 2007-2013 era tools)

This project is deliberately vintage. A sysop can build every target with
period-correct tooling and never touch a modern dependency (except the emulator
*host*, which should be current - see the note). Everything lands in a tight
2007-2013 window.

| Piece                | Version / target                 | Era        |
|----------------------|----------------------------------|------------|
| Compiler             | Free Pascal **2.6.2**            | Feb 2013   |
| Windows target       | Windows XP, 32-bit (PE32 i386)   | 2001+      |
| Linux target         | Debian 4/5 (Etch/Lenny), i386    | 2007-2009  |
| macOS target         | `i386-darwin` (32-bit Intel)     | 2006-2011  |
| macOS SDK (to link)  | **MacOSX10.6.sdk** (Snow Leopard)| 2009       |
| macOS test emulator  | QEMU (Intel) + **Mac OS X 10.6** | guest=2009 |

Why these pair up: FPC 2.6.2 (2013) predates Apple Silicon, so it targets
PowerPC and 32-bit/64-bit Intel Darwin, not ARM. Our i386 target needs the
**10.6** SDK (newer SDKs dropped 32-bit) and runs on **Intel** macOS 10.6-10.14
(32-bit Intel binaries stop running after 10.15 Catalina). Snow Leopard 10.6 is
the sweet spot: it is the SDK era AND a clean 32-bit-Intel runtime, so what you
link and what you test are the same vintage.

### Testing a Darwin build in an emulator
Note two DIFFERENT QEMU targets - pick by CPU:
- **Intel macOS (what runs our i386-darwin binary):** `qemu-system-x86_64` with
  an old Intel OS X (10.6 Snow Leopard .. 10.12). The practical guide is the
  **royalgraphx/LegacyOSXKVM** project on GitHub. Note: Snow Leopard's 32-bit
  installer is finicky under QEMU TCG; the common workaround is a pre-installed
  10.6 disk image rather than installing from scratch.
- **PowerPC macOS (only if you add a `powerpc-darwin` target):** `qemu-system-ppc`
  runs Mac OS 9 .. OS X 10.5. The **E-Maculation wiki**
  (emaculation.com/doku.php/ppc-osx-on-qemu-for-windows) is the reference.

Sources: QEMU itself from **qemu.org**. The emulator *program* can (and should)
be a current build - a modern QEMU runs an old guest OS more reliably than an
old QEMU would. Only the *guest OS* needs to be period-correct. As always, the
macOS guest image / install media is Apple's; supply your own (same licensing
note as the SDK section above).

## Darwin note: cNetDB / fcl-net

The network unit `m_io_Sockets` uses FPC's `cNetDB` (from the `fcl-net` package)
on all UNIX targets, including Darwin. A complete FPC Darwin installation builds
`fcl-net` as part of its normal package build, so `cNetDB` is present automatically.
If you build against a minimal/partial Darwin unit set and hit
`Can't find unit cNetDB used by m_io_Sockets`, compile it once from FPC source:

    ppc386 -Tdarwin -Amacho -Mobjfpc \
           -Fu<i386-darwin-units> -FU<output-dir> \
           -Fi<fpc-src>/packages/fcl-net/src \
           <fpc-src>/packages/fcl-net/src/cnetdb.pp

then place `cnetdb.ppu`/`cnetdb.o` in your i386-darwin units directory. This
affects every socket-using unit (nodespy_term, mis_client_smtp, mis_client_binkp,
fidopoll), not just one.

## Cross-platform text file convention

All documentation/reference .txt files in this project use:
- CRLF line endings (native on DOS/Windows; tolerated by modern macOS/Linux)
- No byte-order mark (a UTF-8 BOM breaks DOS and older tools)
- Plain ASCII in prose; CP437 high bytes ONLY inside actual ANSI art / display
  files, never in reference docs

This keeps whatsnew.txt, mystic_wiki_reference.txt, and wiki_docs/*.txt readable
identically on DOS, Windows, macOS, and Linux, and on the board itself.
